"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/855763","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-14","<p>The information requested is not available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p>Responsibility for Tax Credits statistics lies with Her Majesty’s Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC).</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-03-14T17:12:51.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/855763/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/855763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/855763/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-05","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much has been spent on the childcare element of (a) tax credits and (b) universal credit in (i) total and (ii) in each region in each of the past five years.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","131068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/855764","Department for Education","false","2018-03-13","<p>The funding and participation data for the Care to Learn scheme is outlined in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Academic year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of young parents claiming Care to Learn support</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Care to Learn funding</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>5,674</p></td><td><p>£24,509,846</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>4,322</p></td><td><p>£18,681,641</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>3,243</p></td><td><p>£14,694,559</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2,802</p></td><td><p>£12,175,798</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>We do not hold this data by region and we are unable to provide figures prior to 2013/14 as the systems which support the Care to Learn scheme have changed.</p><p> </p><p>Care to Learn provides support with childcare costs to young parents who are in education. Young parents are able to claim up to £175 per child per week in London and £160 per child per week elsewhere. This level of support was applicable to all the academic years quoted above.</p><p> </p><p>The data shows that numbers taking up this support have fallen in recent years. A review of the scheme found this to be driven by a reduction in teenage pregnancy rates as well as an overall fall in the number of 16-19 year olds. The Care to Learn scheme is demand led and the department has no direct influence over the number of students that apply for the support.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-03-13T18:10:16.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/855764/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/855764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/855764/answer","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/855764/answer/previousversion/47050","Biography information for Anne Milton","60","Education","Education","2018-03-05","Care to Learn Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many learners have been supported through Care to Learn funding in each of the last five years; and how much has been spent through that same funding in (a) total (b) in each region in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","131069"
