"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852670","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-08","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has not made any estimates of the potential effect on employment from the future development of the shale gas industry.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-08T15:29:33.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852670/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852670/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-01","Fracking: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent estimate he has made of the number of jobs in the shale gas industry in (a) 2025 and (b) 2030; whether those estimates have changed since estimates for the number of such jobs in those years made in (i) 2012 and (ii) 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","130666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852671","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-06","<p>There has been no assessment made on whether work-related activity includes (a) considering referrals to professional services, (b) researching local self-help centres and support groups appropriate to a claimant’s health condition and (c) looking at the Expert Patient Programme online and listing reasons on how it could benefit a claimant.</p><p> </p><p>Requirements agreed between work coaches and claimants are specifically designed to help the claimants engage with work, in whatever way might be appropriate for that individual. The requirements must be reasonable and they are tailored to the claimant’s individual needs. For many of our claimants work preparation activity involves addressing their particular challenges, which can include managing their health condition. We would not ask a claimant to carry out an activity which would carry a risk to the health of the claimant, nor would we ask for a claimant to undergo medical treatment as part of their requirements. We work hard to build supportive and open relationships with our claimants so that we can agree support tailored in the most effective possible way.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-03-06T16:28:21.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852671/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852671/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-01","Department for Work and Pensions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to her Department's guidance, Advice for decision-making: staff guide, updated on 15 February 2018, what assessment she has made of whether work-related activity includes (a) considering referrals to professional services, (b) researching local self-help centres and support groups appropriate to a claimant’s health condition and (c) looking at the Expert Patient Programme online and listing reasons on how it could benefit a claimant.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","130667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852672","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-08","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to the answer I provided to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=125103" target="_blank">125103</a> on 01 February 2018.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-03-08T11:15:54.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852672/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852672/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the effect of the roll-out of Universal Credit on levels of child poverty.","false","Biography information for Mohammad Yasin","Bedford","Mohammad Yasin","130668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852673","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-08","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>However, people with disabilities, including deaf people, benefit from many DFID programmes. For example, through the Girls Education Challenge, DFID supported over 40,000 girls with disabilities, including girls who are deaf, to access an education in countries including Kenya and Uganda.</p><p> </p><p>Through the Disability Catalyst Programme, the UK supports Disabled Persons Organisations to advocate for the rights of deaf people in developing countries including Haiti and Rwanda, including projects preventing violence and advocating for access to education and employment.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","130670","2018-03-08T16:41:36.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852673/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852673/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-01","Developing Countries: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much funding her Department has allocated to deafness programmes in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","130669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852674","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-08","<p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>However, people with disabilities, including deaf people, benefit from many DFID programmes. For example, through the Girls Education Challenge, DFID supported over 40,000 girls with disabilities, including girls who are deaf, to access an education in countries including Kenya and Uganda.</p><p> </p><p>Through the Disability Catalyst Programme, the UK supports Disabled Persons Organisations to advocate for the rights of deaf people in developing countries including Haiti and Rwanda, including projects preventing violence and advocating for access to education and employment.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","130669","2018-03-08T16:41:36.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852674/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/852674/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-01","Developing Countries: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much his Department has allocated to deafness programmes in each country for which aid was provided in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","130670"
